{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568053","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568053"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:09:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19460"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19460","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19460"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.48,0.17,0.1,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12187"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84794"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12187"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19460"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69090"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"20"},{"type":"tags","id":"21"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6549"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"28845"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30590"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"84794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/84794"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents to the surgical clinic with a 1.5 cm ulcer on the lateral edge of his right fifth toe. He has a history of type 2 diabetes mellitus and denies any preceding trauma. His medications include metformin, gliclazide and empagliflozin. He has never smoked.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His right foot reveals a 1.5 cm ulcer over the lateral edge of the fifth toe with surrounding cellulitis. Neurological examination demonstrates glove-stocking paraesthesia to the level of the right mid-foot. His dorsalis pedis and posterior tibial pulses are present bilaterally.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests show a glycated haemoglobin (HbA1c) of 12%. Toe pressure measurements and ankle-brachial index are performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best explains why toe pressures are more accurate than ankle-brachial index in the assessment of this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Toe pressures are more accurate as measurements are taken closer to the pathology","Calcification of lower limb arteries makes ankle-brachial index unreliable","Calcification of toe digital arteries makes ankle-brachial index unreliable","Ankle-brachial index is less accurate as measurements are taken further from the pathology","Ankle-brachial index is contraindicated due to arteriovenous fistulas"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features of a neuropathic diabetic foot ulcer and poorly controlled diabetes. When assessing peripheral vascular disease in diabetic patients, both ankle-brachial index (ABI) and toe pressures are typically measured, but toe pressures are often more reliable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcification of lower limb arteries\u003C/strong\u003E is common in patients with diabetes and chronic kidney disease. This arterial calcification (M\u00f6nckeberg\u0027s arteriosclerosis) makes vessels less compressible, resulting in falsely elevated ABI measurements. This can mask underlying peripheral arterial disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EToe pressures are more accurate as measurements are taken closer to the pathology\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The location of measurement is not the primary reason for improved accuracy - it is the reduced likelihood of calcification in digital vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcification of toe digital arteries\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect because digital arteries are typically spared from significant calcification, which is why toe pressures remain reliable.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnkle-brachial index is less accurate as measurements are taken further from the pathology\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. The distance from the pathology does not affect the accuracy of these measurements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnkle-brachial index is contraindicated due to arteriovenous fistulas\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. While arteriovenous fistulas can affect blood flow measurements, they are not a common consideration in diabetic foot assessment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal toe pressure is \u0026gt;70 mmHg, with critical ischaemia defined as \u0026lt;30 mmHg. A normal ABI ranges from 0.9-1.3, but in diabetic patients, values \u0026gt;1.3 suggest arterial calcification and should prompt toe pressure measurement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Arterial calcification in diabetes can falsely elevate ankle-brachial index measurements, making toe pressures more reliable.","Diabetic patients should have both ankle-brachial index and toe pressure measurements to assess peripheral vascular disease.","Neuropathic diabetic ulcers typically occur at pressure points with loss of protective sensation."],"references":["Tehan P et al. Measurement of toe systolic pressures: a technique paper. Wound Practice and Research 2021; 29(3):148-153."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69090"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19460"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"69090","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/69090"},"attributes":{"create